## AppThemeBinding in .NET MAUI

**XAML — use `AppThemeBinding` markup extension:**

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.MainPage"
             BackgroundColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=#FFFFFF, Dark=#1C1C1E}">

    <VerticalStackLayout Padding="20" Spacing="16">

        <Label Text="Welcome"
               FontSize="28"
               TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=#000000, Dark=#FFFFFF}" />

        <Label Text="This page reacts to system theme."
               FontSize="16"
               TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=#444444, Dark=#BBBBBB}" />

        <Button Text="Click Me"
                BackgroundColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=#6200EE, Dark=#BB86FC}"
                TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=#FFFFFF, Dark=#000000}" />

    </VerticalStackLayout>
</ContentPage>
```

The framework reads the device's current theme and picks `Light` or `Dark` automatically—no event wiring needed. When the user toggles their system theme, bound properties update in real time.

---

**C# equivalent — `SetAppTheme` extension method:**

```csharp
public class MainPage : ContentPage
{
    public MainPage()
    {
        // Page background
        SetAppTheme(BackgroundColorProperty, Colors.White, Color.FromArgb("#1C1C1E"));

        var title = new Label { Text = "Welcome", FontSize = 28 };
        title.SetAppTheme(Label.TextColorProperty, Colors.Black, Colors.White);

        var subtitle = new Label { Text = "This page reacts to system theme.", FontSize = 16 };
        subtitle.SetAppTheme(Label.TextColorProperty,
            Color.FromArgb("#444444"), Color.FromArgb("#BBBBBB"));

        var button = new Button { Text = "Click Me" };
        button.SetAppTheme(Button.BackgroundColorProperty,
            Color.FromArgb("#6200EE"), Color.FromArgb("#BB86FC"));
        button.SetAppTheme(Button.TextColorProperty, Colors.White, Colors.Black);

        Content = new VerticalStackLayout
        {
            Padding = 20, Spacing = 16,
            Children = { title, subtitle, button }
        };
    }
}
```

`SetAppTheme(BindableProperty, lightValue, darkValue)` does exactly what `AppThemeBinding` does in XAML.

---

**Key points:**

| Concern | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Reacts live** | Both approaches update automatically when the OS theme changes |
| **Scope** | Works on any `BindableProperty` (colors, images, strings, etc.) |
| **Override theme** | Set `Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark` to force a theme |
| **Detect current** | Read `Application.Current.RequestedTheme` |
| **Scale up** | For many shared colors, define them in `ResourceDictionary` with `AppThemeBinding` so you only declare values once |
